Filter transmission curves in two-column, space-delimited format with no header line.

Columns must be
  1) Wavelength (nanometers)
  2) Filter transmission coefficient


A published collection of filter curve is available on the SVO filter profile webpage (confirm their wavelength units):
    https://svo2.cab.inta-csic.es/theory/fps/

How they're used:

    When the user defines the "filter" variable in their parameters.txt file using the exact same name as the filenames here,
      the light curve building code will convert all wavelengths in these files into Blackbody fluxes using the Subs::planck() function,
      then apply a weighted mean using the transmission coefficients to obtain an effective blackbody flux for the filter in use,
      then finally interpolate these blackbody fluxes along a temperature grid defined in the cpp-lcurve/src/light_curve_comp.cc file.
    This returns a single filter-integrated blackbody flux instead of a single-wavelength blackbody flux.
      
      
    To use the sdss_gprime.txt filter curve, you must specify "filter=sdss_gprime" in your parameters.txt file.
    If you do not wish to use integrated flux, then you should set "filter=none"
